diff:1613861268:1613859663:=22,23c22,23%0a%3c !Presence of Uncommon Consonants: English and Hausa %0a%3c %0a---%0a> !Glottalized Consonants in English and Hausa %0a> %0a30,31c30,31%0a%3c Lack of uncommon consonants in Hausa vs the [θ] found in English%0a%3c %0a---%0a> How English and Hausa differ in their use of glottalized consonants%0a> %0a37,50c37,47%0a%3c Some consonants are only rarely employed in languages. These are referred to as the 'Uncommon Consonants:' clicks, labial-velars, 'th', and pharyngeals.%0a%3c %0a%3c Clicks make a self-explanatory noise by expanding an air pocket trapped between the mouth and tongue until it releases, causing a noise. Commonly used for communication, but only rarely a linguistic feature.%0a%3c %0a%3c Labial-Velar involve the combination of two different plosive noises (ie [g͡b]) by pressing the tongue to tongue places while releasing the plsoive noise, thereby generating them simultaneously.%0a%3c %0a%3c Phyrangeals are produced when moving the root of the tongue so far back it occupies or stops the pharynx (which is the space above the larynx) during production.%0a%3c %0a%3c 'Th' sounds are fricatives made by placing the tongue against the top teeth and softening the airstream (as opossed to a [s] which lets the airstream hit the teeth).%0a%3c %0a%3c English only employs the 'th' sound out of these, whereas Hausa does not employ any. Note that Hausa is adjacent in the world to many languages with labial velars.%0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly, while 'Th'and Phyrangeals originate from around the world, Labial-velars and Clicks are found almost exclusively in West and South Africa. Why did certain uncommon consonants develop in isolated areas only as opposed to others which developed concurrently in many families?%0a%3c %0a---%0a> The glottal folds are responsible for large variations in vowels. We have learned about voiced and unvoiced consonants as the two primary glottal fold configurations. There are other less common configurations known as glottalized consonants, which involves 3 separate categories:%0a> %0a> Ejective Stops, which involve the upward movement of the larynx with the closing of the glottal folds, creating a quick plosive noise. Written such as [p'] for the bilabial ejective stop.%0a> %0a> Implosives, which involve the downward movement of the larynx, creating inwards airflow to the mouth, creating a noise that ends sharper. Written such as [ɠ] for the voiced velar implosive.%0a> %0a> Glottalized Resonants, which involve free air flow with a slightly tighter constriction of the glottal folds than non-glottalized. Written such as [m'] for the glottalized bilabial nasal.%0a> %0a> English does not make any distinction with glottalized consonants, however, Hausa, a language found primarily in Nigeria and the Sahel, makes use of both ejective stops and implosives, but not resonants. %0a> %0a> It is fairly uncommon for a language to use ejective and implosives together as Hausa does (resonants are even more uncommon). This is interesting because one would think that having some glottalized constants would make it more likely to see other glottalized consonants from increased muscle control. Do all three of these consonant types develop independently, or together?%0a
