diff:1613859663:1613859663:=1,77d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Glottalized Consonants in English and Hausa %0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: Thomas_H_K%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c How English and Hausa differ in their use of glottalized consonants%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c The glottal folds are responsible for large variations in vowels. We have learned about voiced and unvoiced consonants as the two primary glottal fold configurations. There are other less common configurations known as glottalized consonants, which involves 3 separate categories:%0a%3c %0a%3c Ejective Stops, which involve the upward movement of the larynx with the closing of the glottal folds, creating a quick plosive noise. Written such as [p'] for the bilabial ejective stop.%0a%3c %0a%3c Implosives, which involve the downward movement of the larynx, creating inwards airflow to the mouth, creating a noise that ends sharper. Written such as [ɠ] for the voiced velar implosive.%0a%3c %0a%3c Glottalized Resonants, which involve free air flow with a slightly tighter constriction of the glottal folds than non-glottalized. Written such as [m'] for the glottalized bilabial nasal.%0a%3c %0a%3c English does not make any distinction with glottalized consonants, however, Hausa, a language found primarily in Nigeria and the Sahel, makes use of both ejective stops and implosives, but not resonants. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is fairly uncommon for a language to use ejective and implosives together as Hausa does (resonants are even more uncommon). This is interesting because one would think that having some glottalized constants would make it more likely to see other glottalized consonants from increased muscle control. Do all three of these consonant types develop independently, or together?%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: :)%0a%3c (:Category: TypologyOfPhoneticContrasts:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
